metadata.name: WTBS: Olympics Poster Edition #371
metadata.description:
WTBS: Olympics Poster Edition is our official collaboration with Jeres, who was kind enough to work with us in support of the show. The project leans into classic Olympic poster design motifs, embellished by Jeres' signature approach to color and shape. Huge thanks to Jeres for donating their time and enthusiasm to this one, we hope you enjoy it!

As with all WTBS projects, your minting will directly support the podcast and keep us going (and more importantly, collecting!). Our goal is to keep the show free from ads and fully supported by the community, your donations and contributions continue to make that possible. Thank you in advance to everyone who chooses to mint!

Jeres: I love vintage posters. When going to second-hand shops, flea markets or wherever people are selling their used goods, I’m always on the lookout for what people used to hang on their walls. Bauhaus-inspired posters, socialist propaganda, Nagel prints, anything art deco, etc.. but whenever I come across something Olympics inspired I always feel like I hit pay dirt. There’s something about the clean, simple design being used to show people coming together along with the undertones of human excellence that just feels special. And circles. I love circles. I hope you enjoy this collection as much as I enjoyed putting it together with Trinity and Will.

Approximate rarity notes:
5%: Gold Edition
10%: Silver Edition
15%: Bronze Edition

metadata.name: Explora ex machina #1
metadata.description:
This is the fourth in series of works where we pay homage to Ken Knowlton, scientist and computer graphic pioneer and artist who passed on June 16, 2022. Ken Knowlton developed the famous EXPLOR language, (Explicit 2-D Patterns, Local Operations, and Randomness) while at Bell Labs. He published a paper describing it in 1975 entitled: MINI-EXPLOR, A FORTRAN-Coded Version of the EXPLOR Language for Mini (and larger) Computers. (https://dl.acm.org/doi/10.1145/988049.988052)

Explora ex machina is about exploring EXPLOR. In many ways the EXPLOR language is a snapshot in time (1975) where its capabilities were limited by the technology of the era its was created.  Christopher Scussel and I are working on modernizing MINI-EXPLOR, he is working on the engine and I’m trying to put it through aesthetic trials. That’s exactly what this work is all about. The trick going forward will be to make it a usable creative tool without changing its character.

About this image. Back to the original EXPLOR picture plane size of 140x140,  5x5 pixel “cells” and 4 color palettes. The goal is to keep the EXPLOR retro vibe.

Explora ex machina is a set of some random number of three “primitives” chosen in no particular order. The members of the set consist of: A ribbon cable, a doughnut or “bit” (reminiscent of the original core memory of older machines), and single threads or wires. The things you would see if you opened up an old mainframe.

In EXPLOR drawing order is important. Each primitive has its own random variables which alter its appearance and its own rules for interacting with the background on to which it is placed. 

The ribbon cable is a group of cells drawn contiguously along a horizontal sinusoidal path. The cable width is a variable chunk of its defining block. With EXPLOR you can always see the block, placed here in the upper right corner of the picture plane. 

The bit consists of concentric rings drawn by a circle algorithm. The number of rings is fixed but their radii randomly scale. The colors of the rings cycle through the color palette.

Finally the vertical threads are single sinusoidal strands that visually tie the components of the composition together. The parameter of the threads’ curves and colors are random.

We continue to honor the passing of Ken Knowlton with this NFT series. Here is an opportunity to collect an example image from the famous program he authored now updated by Scussel and Kolomyjec. A true piece of Computer Graphic Art history with a modern twist.

(c)2022 Dr. Bill Kolomyjec and Christoper Scussel. All rights reserved.

metadata.name: ASTRONOMICAL #15
metadata.description:
Define your own galaxy.
How will you choose to orient the numerous, or sparse, planets?
What palette might be the topic of discussion on the James Webb Space Telescope's next discovery? 
Mould your central planet into the next ASTRONOMICAL phenomenon.

Every aspect of every aspect is randomized: the location, opacity and size of stars. The colours, division, and size of the central planet. The number and location of curves, as well as the size, colour and number of planets along each one. The thickness of the border, and the strength of the effects.

100% chance of 1 ring, 10% chance of two rings and 1% chance of three rings around the central planet.

Made with p5.js.

metadata.name: Bonsai Bonanza #316
metadata.description:
In previous works, I was attracted by the idea of ​​the domestication of plants.
According to Wikipedia, the purposes of bonsai are primarily contemplation for the viewer, and the pleasant exercise of effort and ingenuity for the grower. By contrast with other plant cultivation practices, bonsai is not intended for production of food or for medicine. Instead, bonsai practice focuses on long-term cultivation and shaping of one or more small trees growing in a container.
I pressume that the main intention is aesthetic. The beauty. Because we love beautiful things.
It is very interesting how we modify certain creatures for our sake of satisfaction.

May this collection brings you good fortune.

metadata.name: Rain Ritual #201
metadata.description:
Every windy gust.... every breeze, gave the restless grasses a chance to spread their suggestive rumours, their spurious gossip. All the while, Old Ones of the field towered above, chanting to their wrathful Sky God for more rain.... Always more rain. 

Instructions 
Intended for high resolutions. Use the following keys once render is complete, to export (letters export without a border) 

Square mode 
   1 (q) : 2048x2048  
   2 (w) : 3072x3072 
   3 (e) : 4096x4096 
   4 (r) : 5120x5120 

Landscape mode (increases spacing between objects to preserve aspect ratio) 
   5 (t) : 2560x1440 
   6 (y) : 3840x2160 
   7 (u) : 5128x2880 
   8 (I) : 7680x4320 

Note: Generated textures are resolution dependant, resulting in very slight differences across resolutions. Composition however, remains identical. 

Browsers 
Tested with Chrome, Edge and Firefox on Windows, Chrome on Mac. 
Note for Firefox users : Ensure "Use hardware acceleration" is ticked – Found in Settings / Performance. Other advanced settings to enable include : gfx.canvas.accelerated,  gfx.direct2d.force-enabled and gfx.offscreencanvas.enabled - Unfortunately even with these, Firefox appears slower than other browsers.  

Shoulders of Giants [license text and links included in source] 
- Aristid Lindenmayer – Formal L-System language (Tree routine) 
- P5.js - Creative coding framework 
- JS Topology Suite "JSTS", a port of Java Topology Suite "JTS" - High-level Geometry library 

Additional JS functions 
- Epistemex - Cardinal Splines library (Curve calculations) 
- MaetDol - K-Means library (Tree foliage routine) 
- Angelos Chalaris - Directed Graphs Tutorial (Tree routine)

metadata.name: Traffic #21
metadata.description:
Traffic is a companion piece to Scaffold. Whilst Scaffold was intended to capture a moment in time of a single mind, Traffic aims to represent a shared moment in a community.

Outputs can be beautiful, but can also be chaotic. They can be comprised of many contributions, but a single voice may drown out many others.

All royalties go to the original minter.

Keyboard commands:

s - save as png
h - toggle high resolution 
b - toggle background texture
a - switch aspect ratio
r - new moment

metadata.name: ASSEMBLING MACHINE #36
metadata.description:
The machine never sleeps.
Build. Construct. Develop. Create. Form. Produce. Generate. Repeat.
---------------
Collectors at the highest tier (125 tez) may claim a signed 8”x10” print of their mint. Please look for details about prints on Twitter (@teaboswell), or contact me directly
---------------
CONTROLS:
A - Toggle loading animation (off by default to improve performance)
S - Download image
Double tap (mobile) - Download image
1-6 - Modify scale (1 = default, 2048 x 2730px, 6 = maximum, 12288 x 16380px (very performance intensive, will take a long time to render))
F - Fit to current screen size
G - Toggle grain overlay
L - Toggle background grid lines
B - Cycle border sizes (0 -> 100 -> 200 -> 300px)

You can modify the x and y url parameters to set a custom size. Note that the image will change to fit the new size, but overall drawing style, colors, etc. will remain the same.
(For example, for a 1000x2000 image, add &x=1000&y=2000)
---------------

metadata.description:
GPT-3 is a machine learning platform that enables developers to train and deploy AI models. It can be used to create generative art, which is the art that is created by algorithms.

The tree algorithm was created by GPT-3.

metadata.name: Unicorn #8864
metadata.description:
All of us have dreams, and everyone would like to meet a fairy, a genie, a wizard, or someone else who will make our dreams come true in a snap of a finger or with the wave of a wand. But we're the only ones who can do it. We are those magical unicorns, unique, inimitable, with our own qualities and magical abilities.
These unicorns are the visualization of our inner selves that makes our dreams come true. An embodiment of all the best with a huge positive magical power.

metadata.name: Computed Scenery #56
metadata.description:
I spent my college years living in a place near mountains and the sea. It was my dream to use mathematics and algorithms to describe a fantastically beautiful world in my hometown.

This piece was originally an audio-visual artwork. But after a few years, I rewrote it as a piece of generative art.

I hope you will like it.

- Made with P5js
- Press 's' to save the artwork

metadata.name: Happenings #196
metadata.description:
Inspired by the chaos and imperfectly beautiful dynamics of parenting and life, 'Happenings' is the embodiment of the messiness, the unexpected and playful experiences that allow for the greatest depths of connection with our children.

Our intention was to evoke our deepest and most personal feelings as parents of young ones navigating the challenges of the pandemic while immersing ourselves in the Web3 arena.

This collection is Jimena + Marcos’ first generative art collection in the Tezos blockchain via FX Hash, and consists of 222 1/1 artworks created with javascript.

metadata.name: an abstract concept #13
metadata.description:
I often try to duplicate my IRL analog abstract painting in code, and this, like my previous mint "a fleeting moment," is an attempt at that. Or it started that way. As is usual with such things, it quickly took on a life of its own. 

The algorithm itself consists of three layers of the main particle abstraction, which comes in five different styles, and roughly eight layers of the "texture," which comes in three styles. The palette consists of the background color and three colors for the particle algorithm. The texture is always drawn with the first of those three colors (the "base" color.) 

The result is indicative of my normal painting style (I almost always use three color layers over a background color, and paint with a spatula, palette knife, or cake knife) but is its own unique look.
